Conservative management of localized prostatic cancer.

Whitmore WF Jr(1), Adolfsson J, Steineck G.

Author information:
(1)Department of Surgery, Memorial Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center, New York, New 
York 10021.

Radical prostatectomy (RP), irradiation (RT), early endocrine therapy (EET), and 
expectant treatment (DT) are strategies for the management of clinically 
localized prostatic cancer. EET has not been systematically studied, but 
warrants prospective exploration. DT in uncontrolled studies results in 
disease-specific survival rates at 10 years that appear comparable to those 
achieved following RP or RT and may be considered a management option in 
patients with limited life expectancy. Serial observations in untreated patients 
provide a clinical indication of the rate of tumor progression, but better 
indicators of growth rate, metastatic potential, and responsiveness to a 
particular therapy are needed. Decision analysis may ultimately provide a 
practical supplement to clinical judgment in the choice of treatment.

